Employee returned to vaccination area at 13:45, reported mild intermittent tingling in hands and feet bilat; primarily feet and primarily when he sat down. Reported he had been continuing doing his duties without difficulty but didn't know if he should be concerned. Noted blotchiness on forearms under different lighting when he went to restroom. Blotchiness mild to moderate and mostly resolved before he left. VS at 14:02: BP 136/69, O2 99%, P 80, T 36.7. Reported tingling mostly resolved if he stretches his legs out some. Reported anxiety over "the whole thing. It's just weird and I've been excited about the vaccine". Reviewed S/S to be aware of, when to seek medical attention and that he was feeling completely stable and comfortable before he left. Positively reactive to increased information and seeing improvement in blotchiness. Left at 14:08.

I had difficulty concentrating and focusing on Wednesday evening, a little over a day after getting my first shot. The focusing/concentration issues went away by the next morning when I woke up, however I have been feeling very tired physically since then. I'm yawning all day and have very little energy or interest in doing things I need to be doing. I'm not certain that this is vaccine related, and I'm not super concerned about it yet as I'm on Spring break from school, but I start virtual classes again on Monday and will be concerned if I'm still super tired. If it doesn't go away by next weekend, I will likely resubmit/add on to this report if that is an option. It is not a serious concern yet so I haven't contacted medical professionals yet, but I thought it might be a good idea to at least report that this has been going on to VAERS

Starting at 8pm on vaccination day I got loopy and disoriented, and had a hard time speaking intelligibly. I also had trouble with balance and fine motor skills. Had some personality changes too: became very moody with erratic mood swings. The next day I slept all day because of exhaustion and aches. When I woke up on Wednesday (36hrs later) I was literally screaming in pain because of how bad my arm and shoulder hurt. It hurt to move it, and hurt not to move it. It was excruciating and ibuprofen didn't seem to help at all. Throughout Wednesday I could hardly move my left arm. Getting dressed or washing my hair was very difficult and very painful. I was also still very uncoordinated. My left armpits lymph nodes were so swollen that (1) it filled in my entire armpit so there was no more pit, just a very soft bulge, and (2) the fluid extended all the way to my chest and it looked like I had one breast and one pec.

Vivid/lucid dreaming with bright lights; Vivid/lucid dreaming with bright lights; light headiness a feeling that i would pass out or die and tingling and shakimg; tingling and shaking throughout his body; tingling and shaking throughout his body; As he remained in a confused mental state; received bnt162b2 first dose on 10Mar2021, second dose on 24Mar2021; received bnt162b2 first dose on 10Mar2021, second dose on 24Mar2021; nocturnal panic attack with unknown trigger; Occasinally elevated blood pressure; slight markings of dehydration; hangover; This is a spontaneous report from a Contactable consumer (patient). A 40-year-old male patient received bnt162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, brand: Pfizer), second dose via an unspecified route of administration, administered in arm left on 24Mar2021 11:30 at age of 40-year-old (Lot Number: ER8733) at single dose for COVID-19 immunization. The most recent COVID-19 vaccine was administered at Facility of Doctor's office/urgent care. Medical history included gout, anxiety, gastrooesophageal reflux disease, 'espoghutis'. The patient did not have allergies to medications, food, or other products. Concomitant medication within 2 weeks of vaccination included omeprazole; allopurinol; escitalopram. The patient did not receive any other vaccines within 4 weeks prior to the COVID vaccine. The patient previously took first dose of bnt162b2 via an unspecified route of administration, administered in arm left on 10Mar2021 11:30 at age of 40-year-old (Lot Number: En6206) at single dose for COVID-19 immunization. On 02Apr2021, the patient had vivid/lucid dreaming with bright lights and unusual feelings as he initially fell asleep. He was able to wake himself up but remained in between sleep and awake. This was accompanied by light headiness a feeling that he would pass out or die and tingling and shaking throughout his body as he remained in a confused mental state while his wife called an ambulance. In 2021, his vitals were fine with occasionally elevated blood pressure and slight markings of dehydration ( during the day following his second dose he felt like he had a bad hangover). The ER doctor thought the most likely explanation is sometime of nocturnal panic attack with unknown trigger. He had not previously sufferer anything like it. The events were reported as non-serious. The adverse events result in doctor or other healthcare professional office/clinic visit and emergency room/department or urgent care. The patient received treatment for the adverse events which included: drugs to calm, fluids. Prior to vaccination, the patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19. Since the vaccination, the patient had not been tested for COVID-19. The outcome of the events light headiness, tingling and shaking throughout his body, confused mental state, nocturnal panic attack with unknown trigger, vivid/lucid dreaming with bright lights, elevated blood pressure, slight markings of dehydration, hangover were resolving. Information on lot/batch number obtained. Further information is expected.

Brain fog; Dizziness; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient). A 40-year-old male patient received the second dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, Lot number and expiration date were not reported) on the left arm on 05Apr2021 (10:30) as a single dose, with route of administration unspecified, for COVID-19 immunization. The patient's medical history was not reported. Concomitant medications included venlafaxine hydrochloride (EFFEXOR), allopurinol, omeprazole (PRILOSEC) and lorazepam. The patient had previously received the first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, Lot number and expiration date were not reported) on the left arm on 15Mar2021 (when the patient was 40 years old) for COVID-19 immunization. On 05Apr2021 (14:00), the patient had brain fog and dizziness. The events had resulted into doctor or other healthcare professional office/clinic visit and emergency room/department or urgent care, and were reported to be serious (causing disability or permanent damage). The patient did not receive any treatment for the reported events. The outcome of the events was not recovered. The patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19 prior to vaccination, and had not been tested post-vaccination. Information on the lot/batch number has been requested.

41 2021-01-20 insomnia After 1st Pfizer shot I experienced the worst headache of my life 4-6 hours after the shot with loca... Read more
Close
After 1st Pfizer shot I experienced the worst headache of my life 4-6 hours after the shot with localized pulsation in my right temporal region prior to the headache. The headache persisted through the night and I could not sleep and did not decrease with over the counter medication, my pain was rated 9/10 to 10/10 in the same area the pulsation happened. This headache continued for 4-6 hours at a severe level than for another 6-8 hours at a moderate to severe level. I ended up checking in at the Emergency department that I worked at after my shift and got labs and CT scan, this was after my symptoms resolved. I thought that I might have had a head bleed and wish I would have gotten my CT earlier when experiencing the symptoms. Close
On March 25, 8 days after the vaccine shot in my left arm, I began experiencing intense pain on the left side of my neck and head. By March 28 the pain had become so excruciating I went to an Urgent Care facility and they sent me to the Emergency Room. While in the ER I had blood tests and a CT scan which all came back negative. I was given Oxycodone-Acetaminophen for the pain and prescribed Cephalexin in case there was some type of infection. They also ruled out Shingles. I continued to have pain and contacted my Primary Care Physicians Office and spoke with one of the Physician Assistants two times the next week. She prescribed Baclofen 10 mg and took me off the Cephalexin and put me on Amoxycillin because we thought the problem might have been an ear infection. The next week I spoke with my Primary Care Physician, and he believed I was suffering from Trigeminal Neuralgia, so he put me on Carbamazepine 200 mg twice a day. That same week, on April 9, I was finally able to meet with the Physician Assistant at the Neurologists office and she also believed I was suffering from Trigeminal Neuralgia. I continued to take the Carbamazepine daily and the Baclofen and Oxycodone-Acetaminophen as needed. On Monday April 12 I informed the nurses at the Neurologist office that I was experiencing several symptoms/side effects that included dizziness, weakness, difficulty swallowing and a pounding heartbeat. The nurses talked with the PA and the PA took me off the Carbamazepine and put me on Oxcarbazepine 150 mg twice a day and she prescribed Methylprednisolone 4 mg. On Thursday April 15 I began to have intense prolonged pain behind my left ear down to the neck and in the Trigeminal nerves in the forehead and top of the head on the left side. I was in so much pain I slept for less than 2 hours. The next morning, I vomited and went to the Emergency Room again. At the ER they treated my pain with a headache IV cocktail that included Ibuprofen, Benadryl, an anti-nausea medication, Fentanyl, and a steroid. Within an hour my pain level dropped from a 9 to a 3 and I was released. The ER prescribed Gabapentin 300 mg (3 times a day) which I started the evening of April 16. I have had less constant pain since leaving the ER and starting the Gabapentin, but I continue to have pain in the Trigeminal nerve areas and neck with some flare ups that reach a 7 out of 10 in pain. I am scheduled for an MRI on April 23 and a visit with the Neurologist on May 10.

Symptoms worsened over the next few days, with pain intensifying and extending down into my hand and up into my armpit and shoulder. I tried ice, Ibuprofen, Acetaminophen, and Vicodin for pain relief, but nothing really helped other than the ice. On Saturday morning (2/27), I visited Urgent Care and was diagnosed as brachial plexis neuritis, aka Parsonage-Turner Syndrome by Dr and prescribed Prednisone and rest. On Sunday evening (2/28), I went to the ER seeking pain relief and second opinion. On Monday (3/1) morning, I was seen by ED doctors, and then three different neurologists. After doing an ultrasound which ruled out vein/artery thrombosis, the neuro team diagnosed Parsonage-Turner Syndrome. They've prescribed Gabapentin, Acetaminophen, and Ibuprofen for pain relief, a follow-up neuro consult, an MRI for next Friday, and an EMG in a few weeks. The right arm pain is less than the left arm pain, but at this point seven days later, I am experiencing neuropathic pain in both arms.

He had unrelenting headache over night that was moderate to severe. He said it kept him awake. It was exacerbated by lying down. Sitting up helped him. It became a migraine which is something he doesn't often experience. Migraines are pretty rare for him. He took 800mg of Advil at 6AM that helped for headache and migraine. The weight of the patient was 250 to 255 pounds. Shaking, sweats, hot and cold flashes, and augmentation of myalgias have resolved. Everything has resolved except for a little headache. In the background he literally had one or two hours of sleep. He thinks that likely precipitated a migraine was increased. Last night he slept literally an hour. He took 800mg of Advil and fell asleep. He is operating on 2 hours of sleep in 48 hours. Most of the stuff is gone except a little headache and expected fatigue. Headache Seriousness Criteria: he would say that it was relatively disabling. He would not have been able to carry on. He wouldn't have been able to operate last night. It would have interfered. It was dissimilar to others. He gets rare migraines. Everything was amplified with a migraine. He certainly felt that. It was fair to say the vaccine precipitated the migraine that was mild or severe. He doesn't want to falsely attribute these things to the vaccine. Causality Headache: precipitated by the vaccine. In the context that he had not slept the night before. He had a nasopharyngeal COVID test and it was negative. He has been in a COVID study where they are looking at combination. They developed a saliva test at (Name). There is a combination of saliva oropharyngeal and immunoglobins. He has been negative multiple times. Within approximately a couple of days from the first of two COVID19 Pfizer injections, I developed a progressive, systemic, neuro/neuro-muscular inflammatory pain response. The inflammation and pain first manifested in my left wrist and hand, greatly worsening recent symptomology that may have been the start of a carpal tunnel syndrome. The inflammation and pain were severe, especially from the early a.m. (3 or 4 in the a.m.) to waking hours. Then, on Monday, March 29, 2021, I saw an orthopaedic for the pains in my wrists and hands, and he prescribed me a steroid for a preliminary diagnose of bilateral carpal tunnel. The inflammation and pain throughout my body decreased considerably after only two doses of the steroids. That led me to seek a consultation with the rheumatologist.
